I'm an older man - getting used to not working full time,  so I sometimes call myself semi retired, but I work part time when work comes along. I've been doing some community teaching recently, and some work on an oral history project. I also volunteer, on and off, with different projects.

My interests include computing, human rights (I helped organise the LGBTI human rights conference in Wellington back a few years ago), economic history, and many other things. I've done privacy and technology work, rights advice work, community work, kids play, community arts, social work. 

I don't smoke, I like cities and visiting museums etc. but also swimming, the gym, walking in the bush, reading, films and the rest. And we can both help give you some information about what to do here in Wellington and in New Zealand.

name: Te Huia - A Private Escape
description:
Private and secluded, the two-bedroom purpose-built Te Huia sits nestled into the hillside and enjoys expansive views over the Pacific Ocean. It is a quiet and peaceful place to relax and unwind. Backing onto a forest reserve you will enjoy a vast variety of native birds around the house. Wander through the bush track and listen to the Kiwi calling at dusk. Amazing white beaches and fantastic hiking trails are close by for the active explorer
Full or semi-catering by private chef available.
neighborhood_overview:
Whangarei Heads is a 6000 ha peninsula and is well known for its outstanding scenic beauty and amazing coastal walks and hikes. The Mt Manaia hike is recognised as one of New Zealand top 14 short walks and Bream Head/Te Whara trail as of of the top 5 day hikes. The views from any of the many trails are simply outstanding.

Bream Head Scenic reserve is a coastal forest reserve. It is a rich archaeological landscape resulting from more than 500 years of Maori occupation.

On the Harbourside there are numerous sheltered beaches and waterways and on the Pacific oCean side you will find the most incredible white sandy beaches. Kilometres of beach!! Ocean Beach is surf-patrolled in summer.

Slightly further you have Tutukaka where boat trips head to the Poor Knights Islands. Most of our visitors do this trip. Highly recommended for a day out.
host_about: After travelling for 12 years working in the super yacht industry we have decided to make beautiful New Zealand home. We live in an amazingly beautiful area and we love sharing it with others. Conservation is a huge part of our work here. Our high end service background reflects in everything we do here and we love sharing our slice of paradise with visitors. Thoroughly enjoy meeting new folks from all over the world.

name: Ann's Cottage - By The Sea!
description:
Cute, self contained cottage just a one minute walk to the beach. Easy to locate with room to park offstreet.
Free wifi.
Less than 10 minutes walk to supermarket, shops and cafes. One hour drive to The Pancake Rocks at Punakaiki and 1.5 hours to Franz Josef Glacier.
neighborhood_overview:
The cottage is situated in a quiet street. Make sure that you take the time to walk out the gate, across the road and along a few houses to gain access to the beach. It's a wild West Coast beach that is great to walk along.
Also take a walk back to the main highway to see the glowworms after dark.

What else can you do while here?

* Take a drive out to Lake Kaniere then on to Hokitika Gorge.
* A walk along the wild beach, check out the amazing driftwood sculptures.
* Fish and chips at Sunset Point and watch the sun go down
* Drive to the pancake rocks at Punakaiki
* At night, visit the glow worm dell 5 mins from the cottage
* Shop at one of the many tourist shops offering every sort of craft. It's a great place to buy gifts to take home.
*Spend time watching jade carving or glassblowing
* Visit the Tree-top Walkway.
* Get some exercise at the Hokitika Town swimming pool. It's heated and covered. Opens at 6am.
host_about:
I'm a traveller by nature so I enjoy hosting other travellers. As well as hosting accommodation  I am a member of AIRBNB EXPERIENCE Hosts providing HOKITIKA HISTORY WALK with Ann. Join me and hear about the gold rush days of the 1860s. 
https://abnb.me/jqMRxGqLYU 
I’m also a member of Pro Guides New Zealand.
I love  to read, knit and garden but never seem to have the time. I’m also an active member of Soroptimists International of Westland.

neighborhood_overview:
Stleonards is harbourside suburb only 7 kms out of the city of dunedin.

It looks over the harbour to the otago peninsula, Harbour cone and Larnock Castle.

There is a local primary school close by with a great children park and also a football field and another park across the road from the lodge.

There is a bus stop within 3 minutes walk with regular buses into town, or down to Port Chalmers which is locally well know port town.

Stleonards is abundant with bird life which you can hear especially in the mornings when the birds are waking up and full of chatter.

Stleonards is a beautiful, peaceful area to spend some time in Dunedin but easily accessable to the city
